    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2602.05746v1</id>
    <title>Learning to Inject: Automated Prompt Injection via Reinforcement Learning</title>
    <updated>2026-02-05T15:14:46Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.05746v1" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.05746v1" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>Prompt injection is one of the most critical vulnerabilities in LLM agents; yet, effective automated attacks remain largely unexplored from an optimization perspective. Existing methods heavily depend on human red-teamers and hand-crafted prompts, limiting their scalability and adaptability. We propose AutoInject, a reinforcement learning framework that generates universal, transferable adversarial suffixes while jointly optimizing for attack success and utility preservation on benign tasks. Our black-box method supports both query-based optimization and transfer attacks to unseen models and tasks. Using only a 1.5B parameter adversarial suffix generator, we successfully compromise frontier systems including GPT 5 Nano, Claude Sonnet 3.5, and Gemini 2.5 Flash on the AgentDojo benchmark, establishing a stronger baseline for automated prompt injection research.</summary>
    <category term="cs.LG" scheme="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom"/>
